To comply with the applicable legal and regulatory obligations, we may disclose data to the relevant institutions in order to comply with the applicable laws and regulations. These institutions may include supervisory authorities, tax authorities, judicial/investigative authorities, such as the police, public prosecutors, as well as courts on their express and legal request.
In all of these cases, we ensure that third parties can only access the personal data that is necessary for their specific tasks.
INDIVIDUALS’ RIGHTS AND HOW TO EXERCISE THEM
You as a data subject have certain rights over your personal data and we as controllers are responsible for fulfilling these rights. Further information about these rights, when they are available and how to exercise them is available below.
YOUR RIGHT TO ACCESS TO PERSONAL DATA
You have the right to obtain a copy of your personal data, as well as other supplementary information available to us. It may help you understand how and why we are using your data, and make sure that we are doing it lawfully.
YOUR RIGHT TO RECTIFICATION/AMENDMENT OF PERSONAL DATA
You have the right to request for your personal data to be amended or rectified where it is inaccurate (for example, if you change your name or address), and to have incomplete personal data completed.
YOUR RIGHT TO ERASURE/RIGHT TO BE FORGOTTEN
You have the right to the erasure of your personal data, which is available to us, but this right is not absolute and only applies in certain circumstances.
You have the right to the erasure of your personal data that is available to us if:
the personal data is no longer necessary in relation to the purpose for which we originally collected or processed it;
we are relying on consent as a legal basis for retaining the data, and you withdraw your consent;
we are relying on legitimate interests as the legal basis for data processing, and you object to the processing of your data, with no overriding legitimate interest for us to continue this processing;
we are processing the personal data for direct marketing purposes and you object to that processing;
your personal data has been processed unlawfully;
your personal data must be erased to comply with a legal obligation that we are subject to.
If you wish your data to be erased (deleted) from the App, please contact us via email: soundid@sonarworks.com.
YOUR RIGHT TO RESTRICT PROCESSING
You have the right to restrict the processing of your personal data, that is, to limit the way that we use your data, in the following circumstances:
for a period enabling us to verify the accuracy of your personal data where you have contested the accuracy of your personal data available to us;
the data has been unlawfully processed and you request restriction instead of erasure;
when your personal data is no longer necessary in relation to the purposes for which we originally collected or processed it, you can request restriction to establish, exercise or defend legal claims;
for a period enabling us to verify whether the legitimate interests relied on by us override your interests where you have objected to the processing based on legitimate interests.
YOUR RIGHT TO OBJECT TO PROCESSING
The right to object to processing allows you to ask us to stop processing your personal data.
You have the absolute right to object to the processing of your personal data if it is for direct marketing purposes.
You have the right to object to the processing of your personal data also when there are other legitimate interests for processing, but then we have to verify whether your interests override the legitimate interests relied on by us.
YOUR RIGHT TO DATA PORTABILITY
The right to data portability gives you the right to receive your personal data that you have provided to us in a structured, commonly used and machine-readable format. It also gives you the right to request that we transmit this data directly to another controller.
The right to data portability only applies when:
the legal basis for the processing of this personal data is consent or for the performance of a contract;
we carry out the processing by automated means.
YOUR RIGHT TO WITHDRAW CONSENT
Where we process personal data based on your consent, you have the right to withdraw consent at any time in the form indicated at the time of giving consent or by sending an email to: soundid@sonarworks.com.
YOUR RIGHT TO LODGE A COMPLAINT
If you have a complaint on how we use your personal data, please contact us via email: soundid@sonarworks.com. We will review and respond to all complaints received.
You also have the right to lodge a complaint with the supervisory authority in your country of residence, place of work or the country in which an alleged infringement of data protection law has occurred. The data protection supervisory authority in the Republic of Latvia is the Data State Inspectorate, contact information:
Blaumaņa iela 11/13-11,
Riga, LV-1011, Latvia
Phone: +371 67 223 131
Email: info@dvi.gov.lv
Website:
https://www.dvi.gov.lv/en/
HOW TO CONTACT US
If you have any questions, comments, complaints or suggestions in relation to data protection or this Privacy Policy, or any other concerns about the way in which we process information about you, please contact us:
Sonarworks SIA
Address: Šmerļa iela 3, Riga, LV-1006, Latvia.
Phone: +371 22337611
Email: soundid@sonarworks.com
SCOPE OF THE PRIVACY POLICY
We may amend the Privacy Policy to remain compliant with any changes in law and/or to reflect changes in the processing of personal data by us. We will alert you about any changes by updating the “Last updated” date of the Privacy Policy.Oct 07, 2021
SoundID Privacy Policy
INTRODUCTION
In this SoundID Privacy Policy (“Privacy Policy”), Sonarworks SIA (“Sonarworks” or “we”), informs you (“you”) about the processing of personal data for which we are responsible in the sense of the applicable legislation, including the General Data Protection Regulation (“GDPR”).
We consider the protection of your privacy and personal data as an important business value. Therefore, we only process your personal data in accordance with this Privacy Policy, and applicable law, including the GDPR.
In the Privacy Policy, we describe why and how we collect and process personal data related to the use of our website, mobile application, online purchases of SoundID software products, and the use of the trial version of our software.
Personal data is any information relating to an identified or identifiable natural person. An identifiable natural person is one who can be identified, directly or indirectly, in particular by reference to an identifier, such as a name, a personal identification number, location data, an online identifier, or to one or more factors specific to the physical, physiological, genetic, mental, economic, cultural or social identity of that natural person.
When we use “you” or “your” in this Privacy Policy, we are referring to the relevant individual who is the subject of the personal data.
WEBSITE VISITORS AND MOBILE APPLICATION USERS
Each time you access us online, we collect the following information about the device you are using: IP address, the request from your browser, the date and time of this request, as well as the status and amount of data transferred by the request. We also collect information about the browser used, the operating system of the device and the Internet service provider.
This data is collected automatically, including via the use of cookies and other tracking technologies when you visit our website.
Cookies are small text files that are dropped on a user’s web browser by the website that the user is viewing. Each cookie contains a small amount of information, such as a unique identifier that links the user to a specific website. Our website may use cookies to track the number of times you have visited the website, to track the number of visitors to the website, to determine and analyze visitors’ use of our websites, to store data that you provide (such as your preferences), and to store technical information related to your interactions with our website. We may also use session cookies, which are deleted when you close your browser, to store your user ID, to facilitate your movement around our websites (particularly in connection with information searches and order placement), and other information used in administering the session.
You can find out more about our use of cookies in our Cookie Policy.
If you use our website without revealing your identity or without providing any personal data, the processing of the above-mentioned information is not considered as processing of personal data within the meaning of the GDPR. If, on the other hand, you perform activities on our website that require the provision of identifiable personal data, we process your data for the purposes and on the legal basis described below.
The purpose of the above-mentioned data processing is to enable appropriate operation of our website, to enable the content of our website to be displayed on your device, to detect and eliminate errors, to determine how our website are used, to make adjustments and improvements to our products, our website, and to personalize your browsing experience by displaying content that is more likely to be relevant and of interest to you.
The legal basis for processing your personal data for the above-mentioned purposes is our legitimate interests, namely, the demand-oriented design of the website, and the provision of network and information security.
